ha-2 adrenergic receptors","Blocks beta adrenergic receptors","Activates peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors","Inhibits angiotensin converting enzyme","Blocks peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClonidine primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating central alpha-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E in the brainstem. This reduces sympathetic outflow from the central nervous system, leading to decreased blood pressure, sedation, and analgesic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other mechanisms are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking beta adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for beta blockers like propranolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would increase rather than decrease blood pressure. Clonidine activates central receptors, not peripheral. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting angiotensin converting enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for ACE inhibitors like enalapril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for drugs like prazosin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reduction in sympathetic outflow caused by clonidine leads to decreased noradrenaline release throughout the body, which explains its therapeutic effects including lowered blood pressure, decreased anxiety, and pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clonidine is a centrally-acting alpha-2 adrenergic receptor agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow from the brain.","The main therapeutic effects of clonidine include reduction in blood pressure, sedation, and analgesia.","Alpha-2 agonists work by inhibiting noradrenaline release in the central nervous system."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52035"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52035"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T09:18:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T09:18:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"